        <!-- History -->
        <div class="history-section">
            <h2>Track Over Time</h2>
            <div class="history-actions">
                <button class="btn" id="save-snapshot">Save Current Snapshot</button>
                <button class="btn btn-outline" id="clear-history">Clear History</button>
            </div>
            <div class="chart-section" id="history-chart-section" style="display:none; margin-bottom:1rem;">
                <div class="history-chart-container">
                    <canvas id="historyChart"></canvas>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="history-list" id="history-list">
                <div class="empty-history">No snapshots saved yet. Click "Save Current Snapshot" to start tracking.</div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- SEO Content -->
        <section class="seo-content">
            <h2>How to Calculate Your Net Worth</h2>
            <p>Your <strong>net worth</strong> is the single most important number in personal finance. It's the clearest snapshot of your financial health — calculated by subtracting everything you owe (liabilities) from everything you own (assets). The formula is straightforward: <strong>Net Worth = Total Assets - Total Liabilities</strong>.</p>
            <p>Unlike income, which only measures cash flow, net worth captures your complete financial picture. Someone earning $200,000 per year with $300,000 in debt has a lower net worth than someone earning $60,000 with $150,000 in savings and no debt. Tracking net worth over time reveals whether you're actually building wealth or just treading water.</p>

            <h2>What Counts as an Asset?</h2>
            <p>Assets are everything you own that has monetary value. When calculating your net worth, include:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Cash &amp; savings:</strong> Checking accounts, savings accounts, money market funds, CDs</li>
                <li><strong>Investments:</strong> Stocks, bonds, mutual funds, ETFs, cryptocurrency, brokerage accounts</li>
                <li><strong>Retirement accounts:</strong> 401(k), 403(b), IRA, Roth IRA, pension values</li>
                <li><strong>Real estate:</strong> Current market value of your home, rental properties, land</li>
                <li><strong>Vehicles:</strong> Cars, motorcycles, boats (use current resale value, not purchase price)</li>
                <li><strong>Other assets:</strong> Business ownership, valuable collectibles, jewelry, life insurance cash value</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>Understanding Your Liabilities</h2>
            <p>Liabilities are debts and financial obligations you owe. Common liabilities include:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Mortgage:</strong> The remaining balance on your home loan (not the original amount)</li>
                <li><strong>Auto loans:</strong> Outstanding car loan balances</li>
                <li><strong>Student loans:</strong> Federal and private student loan balances</li>
                <li><strong>Credit cards:</strong> Total outstanding credit card balances</li>
                <li><strong>Other debt:</strong> Personal loans, medical debt, home equity loans, tax liens</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>Net Worth Benchmarks by Age</h2>
            <p>Based on the Federal Reserve's Survey of Consumer Finances, here's how net worth typically grows by decade. The median (middle value) is a more realistic benchmark than the average, which is skewed by ultra-wealthy individuals:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Under 35:</strong> Median $39,000 — focus on eliminating high-interest debt and building emergency savings</li>
                <li><strong>35–44:</strong> Median $135,600 — career earnings and home equity start compounding</li>
                <li><strong>45–54:</strong> Median $247,200 — peak earning years, maximize retirement contributions</li>
                <li><strong>55–64:</strong> Median $364,500 — final push before retirement, catch-up contributions available</li>
                <li><strong>65–74:</strong> Median $409,900 — highest median net worth age group</li>
                <li><strong>75+:</strong> Median $335,600 — drawdown phase begins, net worth may decline</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <!-- FAQ -->
        <section class="faq-section">
            <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <button class="faq-question">What is net worth and how do you calculate it?</button>
                <div class="faq-answer">Net worth is the total value of everything you own (assets) minus everything you owe (liabilities). Assets include cash, savings, investments, retirement accounts, real estate, and vehicles. Liabilities include mortgages, car loans, student loans, credit card balances, and other debts. The formula is simple: Net Worth = Total Assets - Total Liabilities. A positive net worth means you own more than you owe.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <button class="faq-question">What is the average net worth by age?</button>
                <div class="faq-answer">According to the Federal Reserve's Survey of Consumer Finances, the average and median net worth by age in the U.S. are: Under 35: median $39,000, average $183,500. Ages 35-44: median $135,600, average $549,600. Ages 45-54: median $247,200, average $975,800. Ages 55-64: median $364,500, average $1,566,900. Ages 65-74: median $409,900, average $1,794,600. Age 75+: median $335,600, average $1,624,100. The average is significantly higher due to wealthy outliers, so median is a better benchmark for most people.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <button class="faq-question">What should be included in assets when calculating net worth?</button>
                <div class="faq-answer">Assets to include: liquid assets (checking, savings, money market accounts), investments (stocks, bonds, mutual funds, ETFs, cryptocurrency), retirement accounts (401k, IRA, Roth IRA, pension), real estate (home equity, rental properties), vehicles (cars, boats), and other valuables (jewelry, collectibles, business ownership). Use current market values rather than purchase prices. For your home, use the current estimated value, not the original purchase price.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <button class="faq-question">Can your net worth be negative?</button>
                <div class="faq-answer">Yes, your net worth can be negative. This means you owe more than you own. It's common for young adults, especially those with student loans, to have a negative net worth early in their careers. A negative net worth isn't necessarily alarming if you're actively paying down debt and building assets. The key is that your net worth should be trending upward over time.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <button class="faq-question">How often should I calculate my net worth?</button>
                <div class="faq-answer">Most financial advisors recommend calculating your net worth at least once per quarter (every 3 months) or monthly if you're actively working toward a financial goal. This frequency lets you track progress without getting distracted by short-term market fluctuations. Our calculator saves your history in your browser so you can track trends over time.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <button class="faq-question">How can I increase my net worth?</button>
                <div class="faq-answer">There are two sides to growing net worth: increase assets and decrease liabilities. To increase assets: maximize retirement contributions, invest consistently, build emergency savings, and grow your income. To decrease liabilities: pay off high-interest debt first (avalanche method), make extra mortgage payments, refinance to lower rates, and avoid taking on new consumer debt. The most impactful strategy is usually to simultaneously invest for the long term while aggressively paying down high-interest debt.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <button class="faq-question">Should I include my home in my net worth?</button>
                <div class="faq-answer">Yes, your home should be included in your net worth calculation, but correctly. List your home's current market value as an asset and your remaining mortgage balance as a liability. The difference is your home equity. Some financial planners distinguish between 'total net worth' (including home) and 'investable net worth' (excluding home equity) since you can't easily access home equity for living expenses.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="faq-item">
                <button class="faq-question">What liabilities should I include in my net worth calculation?</button>
                <div class="faq-answer">Include all outstanding debts: mortgage balance (remaining principal), home equity loans/HELOCs, auto loans, student loans, credit card balances, personal loans, medical debt, and any other money you owe. Use the current outstanding balance, not the original loan amount. Do not include monthly bills like utilities or subscriptions — only actual debts where you owe a principal balance.</div>
            </div>
        </section>

